WEBVTT

00:00:01.730 --> 00:00:07.000
Is it showing up?

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Oh, no.

00:00:08.010 --> 00:00:08.740
Can everyone hear me at least?

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:09.190
Okay, good.

00:00:09.430 --> 00:00:09.610
All right.

00:00:10.060 --> 00:00:12.590
Wow, I was not expecting this many people at the end

00:00:12.590 --> 00:00:14.140
of a conference, but we're gonna roll with it.

00:00:14.140 --> 00:00:17.260
I'm still recovering from last night, so we're gonna

00:00:17.260 --> 00:00:17.910
do our best.

00:00:17.910 --> 00:00:20.640
It's Nick's fault, actually, so you can blame

00:00:20.640 --> 00:00:21.070
him.

00:00:21.070 --> 00:00:24.370
So today I wanted to talk about at least my year building

00:00:24.370 --> 00:00:27.150
Bridgie and breaking down the walls of the open social web

00:00:27.150 --> 00:00:27.290
.

00:00:27.290 --> 00:00:29.120
My co-founder, Ryan Barrett, has been doing

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:30.610
it much longer than I have.

00:00:30.610 --> 00:00:32.490
But, yeah, please clap.

00:00:32.490 --> 00:00:33.980
Please clap for Ryan Barrett.

00:00:33.980 --> 00:00:37.750
He's an amazing person.

00:00:37.860 --> 00:00:40.650
But, yeah, it's been a year for me,

00:00:40.650 --> 00:00:44.380
and over the last year, I think we've built a

00:00:44.420 --> 00:00:47.320
lot, but more importantly, I think through that building,

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:50.030
I've learned a lot more about, not just about the

00:00:50.030 --> 00:00:52.730
ecosystems and how they operate and what we need to start caring

00:00:52.730 --> 00:00:55.440
about, but about the way that we can start building as

00:00:55.450 --> 00:00:55.890
well.

00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:58.600
And so I wanted to share some of those findings.

00:00:58.600 --> 00:00:59.700
A little introduction to myself.

00:00:59.700 --> 00:01:00.220
I'm Anuja Huja.

00:01:00.250 --> 00:01:03.420
I'm the Executive Director at AnuSocial.

00:01:03.420 --> 00:01:06.900
We are, our goal is to liberate people's online

00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:09.480
relationships from any one technology.

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:12.180
We're a non-profit, and we've been operating

00:01:12.180 --> 00:01:14.730
for about a month and, a year and change, a

00:01:14.730 --> 00:01:15.380
month.

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:17.720
That was last year.

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:19.080
I also write on my blog, Augment, where I

00:01:19.080 --> 00:01:21.980
'm actually experimenting with a bunch of open social web tools as

00:01:21.980 --> 00:01:22.480
well.

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:24.720
But today I wanted to focus on the work that we've

00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:26.220
been doing at AnuSocial.

00:01:26.220 --> 00:01:30.160
And I always like to start these presentations with the statement that

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:31.440
I remind myself of.

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:34.040
And it's a promise that I make my friends, my

00:01:34.040 --> 00:01:37.050
family, and my colleagues, whenever I introduce them to the

00:01:37.050 --> 00:01:38.860
idea of the open social web.

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:40.720
And it's this concept of, "You can follow anyone

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:44.860
from anywhere in Liefer, another platform at any time."

00:01:44.860 --> 00:01:46.630
And I think the only thing that bothers me about this statement

00:01:46.630 --> 00:01:49.100
is the fact that I always have to add the caveat of

00:01:49.100 --> 00:01:50.860
"kinda." And we all know why.

00:01:50.860 --> 00:01:52.860
I'm not going to get into some reasons.

00:01:52.860 --> 00:01:55.130
But to me, the fact that there's a "k

00:01:55.130 --> 00:01:56.680
inda" really sucks.

00:01:56.680 --> 00:01:58.200
And so the thing that we're trying to do at An

00:01:58.200 --> 00:01:59.860
uSocial is trying to make that "kinda"

00:01:59.860 --> 00:02:03.400
smaller and smaller and smaller over time until it no longer exists

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:03.680
.

00:02:03.680 --> 00:02:05.670
So that's really the basis of the work that we're

00:02:05.670 --> 00:02:06.680
trying to do.

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:11.210
I introduced a version of that idea back last year at At

00:02:11.210 --> 00:02:13.680
mosphere Conference, where I had my presentation, Bridges

00:02:13.680 --> 00:02:14.680
and the Last Network Effect.

00:02:14.680 --> 00:02:16.180
I have a blog post about it.

00:02:16.180 --> 00:02:19.270
I'm not going to recap too much about that presentation in

00:02:19.270 --> 00:02:20.200
particular.

00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:22.960
But at the time when I did that presentation, Anu

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:25.260
Social was like a new foundation.

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:28.170
We just started and a lot of the stuff that I was

00:02:28.490 --> 00:02:30.740
saying on stage were really just like dreams.

00:02:30.740 --> 00:02:32.260
It was more of a multi-year vision.

00:02:32.260 --> 00:02:34.630
And quite frankly, I actually didn't think most of it

00:02:34.630 --> 00:02:36.900
was possible.

00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:39.350
But it turned out that it wasn't a multi-year

00:02:39.350 --> 00:02:42.180
vision because with Ryan Barrett, I was able to do

00:02:42.180 --> 00:02:43.380
it in a single year.

00:02:43.380 --> 00:02:46.560
We actually ended up building most of the stuff that I talked

00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:48.650
about there, or at least the foundational layers of what we

00:02:48.650 --> 00:02:49.300
had to build.

00:02:49.300 --> 00:02:51.970
And so today I wanted to go through some of the highlights

00:02:52.010 --> 00:02:55.060
of that year and specifically talk about some of the lessons I

00:02:55.060 --> 00:02:57.360
learned while we were doing it.

00:02:57.360 --> 00:02:58.340
So let's talk about 2025.

00:02:58.340 --> 00:03:01.940
Our biggest launch of the year was probably Bounce.

00:03:01.940 --> 00:03:04.050
It was an eject button for the OpenSocial Web where

00:03:04.050 --> 00:03:07.560
you could actually migrate your social graph between protocols, keeping all

00:03:07.560 --> 00:03:10.650
of your followers and as many bridged follows as possible.

00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:12.550
This ended up being way bigger than I thought.

00:03:12.550 --> 00:03:14.580
I thought a bunch of protocol nerds would get excited.

00:03:14.580 --> 00:03:16.660
It turned out everyone was excited.

00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:18.900
And we got a bunch of users to try it out for

00:03:18.900 --> 00:03:19.860
the first time.

00:03:19.860 --> 00:03:22.260
People are reviewing their social graphs on there all the time.

00:03:22.260 --> 00:03:23.800
We thought it was just like a neat UI trick.

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:26.820
Turns out people really care about their social graphs and finding out

00:03:26.820 --> 00:03:28.240
how multi-protocol they are.

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:29.380
Very surprising.

00:03:29.380 --> 00:03:30.820
I did not expect that at all.

00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:34.760
But what I learned was we could actually do a lot more

00:03:34.760 --> 00:03:36.490
with the bridge than I originally thought.

00:03:36.490 --> 00:03:39.010
And that was like the biggest lesson for me was this bridge

00:03:39.010 --> 00:03:41.050
is more than just connecting communication.

00:03:41.050 --> 00:03:43.550
We could actually start doing a lot more if we use it

00:03:43.550 --> 00:03:45.220
as the foundation for other products.

00:03:45.220 --> 00:03:47.590
We also launched a settings page.

00:03:47.590 --> 00:03:49.750
We launched a bunch of features for that last year.

00:03:49.750 --> 00:03:50.880
So I don't want to go into each thing.

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:52.980
But the one thing that I wanted to call out that I

00:03:52.980 --> 00:03:57.080
was really excited about was launching app proto block lists on Bridge

00:03:57.080 --> 00:03:59.770
yFed which meant that Fediverse users could take advantage

00:03:59.770 --> 00:04:01.140
of an atmosphere feature.

00:04:01.140 --> 00:04:03.590
And it was the first time where it clicked for me where

00:04:03.590 --> 00:04:06.250
I was like we're not just bridging profiles and posts

00:04:06.250 --> 00:04:06.430
.

00:04:06.430 --> 00:04:10.000
We can actually bridge full-blown features across ecosystems using

00:04:10.010 --> 00:04:10.820
BridgeyFed.

00:04:10.820 --> 00:04:13.690
And like huh, that like really unlocked something in my brain

00:04:13.690 --> 00:04:13.700
.

00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:15.450
And I haven't been able to stop thinking about it since

00:04:15.450 --> 00:04:16.100
we launched it.

00:04:16.100 --> 00:04:19.630
The other thing that we launched was unbridge notifications which if

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:21.860
someone was on the other side of the bridge and they communicated

00:04:21.860 --> 00:04:24.060
with you but they weren't bridged themselves, we couldn

00:04:24.060 --> 00:04:26.350
't show it on your native platform, that sucks.

00:04:26.350 --> 00:04:29.620
There's no visibility of trolls or like people that you actually

00:04:29.620 --> 00:04:31.280
care about interacting with you.

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:34.390
And so we gave you some visibility into that over notifications,

00:04:34.390 --> 00:04:35.020
over your DMs.

00:04:35.020 --> 00:04:37.920
That was a really neat trick that Ryan put together for us

00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:38.180
.

00:04:38.180 --> 00:04:43.060
And then finally we started seeing a bunch of platforms just putting

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:45.620
bridging as a part of their platforms, which was really

00:04:45.620 --> 00:04:45.860
cool.

00:04:45.860 --> 00:04:47.800
One that I want to call out is AltStore.

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:49.780
They're, yeah, clap for AltStore.

00:04:49.780 --> 00:04:51.220
They're freaking amazing.

00:04:51.220 --> 00:04:52.270
They're here by the way.

00:04:52.270 --> 00:04:53.690
You should talk to them.

00:04:53.690 --> 00:04:54.780
They're awesome.

00:04:54.780 --> 00:04:57.380
And the cool thing about AltStore is they're also

00:04:57.380 --> 00:04:59.710
breaking down walls, specifically the walled garden of Apple which

00:04:59.710 --> 00:05:01.670
should have been broken down a long time ago.

00:05:01.670 --> 00:05:03.610
But that's a whole other story.

00:05:03.610 --> 00:05:07.050
We also learned something much bigger this year, at least to

00:05:07.050 --> 00:05:07.460
me.

00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:10.080
It was that Bridgifed actually hosts some of the

00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:12.340
most active users on either network.

00:05:12.340 --> 00:05:15.680
We have about 150,000 accounts on Bridgifed

00:05:15.680 --> 00:05:16.030
now.

00:05:16.210 --> 00:05:19.320
And they are some of the most power user people and they

00:05:19.320 --> 00:05:22.180
don't care about who they're talking to and where they

00:05:22.250 --> 00:05:22.500
are.

00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:24.470
They just want to build a community.

00:05:24.470 --> 00:05:27.290
And all they care about is connecting with people regardless of the

00:05:27.290 --> 00:05:28.260
platform they're on.

00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:31.580
That was just a statement I made last year.

00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:33.770
Turns out like a lot of people agree with that.

00:05:33.770 --> 00:05:38.100
And they're some of the most active users everywhere.

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:40.370
With Bounce as well, I recently learned that we're

00:05:40.370 --> 00:05:43.560
doing about six to eight migrations every month, which is

00:05:43.560 --> 00:05:45.900
a whole lot more than I expected for protocol migration.

00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:48.190
I know that's small numbers when you compare it to the

00:05:48.190 --> 00:05:50.290
crazy numbers that folks are doing on PDS Mover and

00:05:50.290 --> 00:05:50.900
Black Sky.

00:05:50.900 --> 00:05:54.360
But protocol movement's a lot more complicated and a lot more

00:05:54.410 --> 00:05:54.700
scary.

00:05:54.700 --> 00:05:55.630
And we're still in beta.

00:05:55.630 --> 00:05:57.550
And most people don't even know we exist.

00:05:57.550 --> 00:06:00.070
And so eight to ten migrations a month -- sorry,

00:06:00.070 --> 00:06:02.980
six to eight migrations a month kind of blew my mind

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:03.200
.

00:06:03.430 --> 00:06:06.600
But the thing is like these numbers don't really mean a

00:06:06.610 --> 00:06:07.460
lot to me.

00:06:07.460 --> 00:06:09.090
I don't really look -- like Ryan will tell you this

00:06:09.090 --> 00:06:09.200
.

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:09.880
I don't look at DAOs.

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:10.740
I don't look at MAUs.

00:06:10.740 --> 00:06:12.740
I don't really look at the activity that's happening on

00:06:12.870 --> 00:06:13.310
this stuff.

00:06:13.310 --> 00:06:15.380
In fact, I poked Ryan for these numbers like last

00:06:15.380 --> 00:06:18.150
minute because I was like I should probably say some of these

00:06:18.150 --> 00:06:20.780
numbers while I'm on stage as like the executive director.

00:06:20.780 --> 00:06:22.860
But like to me, this stuff doesn't really matter.

00:06:22.860 --> 00:06:25.220
And I think Lawrence Hoff of Connected Spaces wrote it

00:06:25.220 --> 00:06:27.220
better than I could ever say it.

00:06:27.220 --> 00:06:29.540
He said that tools like Bounce suggest the direction of the

00:06:29.540 --> 00:06:33.510
open social web is less about specific protocols and more about expanding

00:06:33.510 --> 00:06:34.380
user agency.

00:06:34.380 --> 00:06:36.260
And I think he kind of nailed it.

00:06:36.260 --> 00:06:38.590
The way that we say it, which I think is less

00:06:38.590 --> 00:06:42.050
creative, is we just think these things should exist and that

00:06:42.050 --> 00:06:42.910
people need them.

00:06:42.910 --> 00:06:44.820
And so we build them because they need them.

00:06:44.820 --> 00:06:46.250
And that's really it.

00:06:46.260 --> 00:06:47.570
Maybe five users are going to use it.

00:06:47.570 --> 00:06:49.700
Maybe 150,000 people are going to use it.

00:06:49.700 --> 00:06:52.790
But to us, these things need to exist because people care

00:06:52.790 --> 00:06:55.700
about connecting with people and using the tools that work best for

00:06:55.700 --> 00:06:56.180
them.

00:06:56.180 --> 00:06:58.110
And so that's why we build the things that we build

00:06:58.110 --> 00:06:58.340
.

00:06:58.340 --> 00:07:01.290
Or as David Pierce on The Verge said about Bounce

00:07:01.300 --> 00:07:03.050
, the idea that I can just pick up my stuff on

00:07:03.050 --> 00:07:05.860
a social network and put it down on another social network,

00:07:05.860 --> 00:07:07.330
like that's it, baby.

00:07:07.590 --> 00:07:08.340
That's the stuff.

00:07:08.340 --> 00:07:13.870
And so this year we're going to keep doing that stuff

00:07:13.870 --> 00:07:17.820
because clearly that stuff matters and we really want to keep doing

00:07:17.820 --> 00:07:18.340
that work.

00:07:18.340 --> 00:07:21.520
And so we've already hit the ground running with 2026

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:21.780
.

00:07:21.780 --> 00:07:23.860
It's only been three months and we've actually launched a

00:07:23.930 --> 00:07:24.550
bunch of stuff.

00:07:24.550 --> 00:07:26.640
I want to quickly go over some of those things.

00:07:26.640 --> 00:07:29.580
For one, we launched the Fediverse version of block lists

00:07:29.580 --> 00:07:30.890
for atmosphere users.

00:07:30.900 --> 00:07:33.010
So now we've bridged a feature from the Fediverse

00:07:33.190 --> 00:07:34.110
over to the atmosphere.

00:07:34.110 --> 00:07:37.160
And we've actually given people some options from reputable sources

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:39.220
who give you full-blown block lists right away.

00:07:39.220 --> 00:07:40.590
So you don't even have to think about it.

00:07:40.590 --> 00:07:42.020
You just go to our page, you click a few block

00:07:42.020 --> 00:07:43.720
lists, and then you don't have to worry about some

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:44.980
of the worst trolls on the Fediverse.

00:07:45.110 --> 00:07:49.140
We also improved unbridge notifications with a full UI.

00:07:49.140 --> 00:07:51.220
So when people interact with you and they can't bridge themselves

00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:53.030
, and they're not bridging themselves, sorry, you

00:07:53.030 --> 00:07:54.730
can just go to the BridgeFed UI.

00:07:54.730 --> 00:07:56.920
You can like, repost, block, or reply to

00:07:56.920 --> 00:07:57.300
them.

00:07:57.300 --> 00:08:01.240
And to me, this was like another unlock because I realized

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:02.740
that, hey, we can actually just do one-way

00:08:02.740 --> 00:08:04.490
interactions once in a while and it's not that big of

00:08:04.490 --> 00:08:04.900
a deal.

00:08:04.900 --> 00:08:07.660
And we also did it in a way where it preserves

00:08:07.660 --> 00:08:08.930
the privacy of the other user.

00:08:08.930 --> 00:08:10.900
Like if they don't want to be on the atmosphere or

00:08:10.900 --> 00:08:12.360
the Fediverse, they don't have to be.

00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:14.500
They can still interact with people on either side.

00:08:14.500 --> 00:08:17.140
And I think that that's really important as well.

00:08:17.140 --> 00:08:19.700
And the biggest, like most exciting thing that's happened so

00:08:19.700 --> 00:08:21.460
far this year, at least for me, was long form

00:08:21.460 --> 00:08:21.950
bridging.

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:23.350
We're now bridging standard.

00:08:23.350 --> 00:08:26.260
site, connecting blogs across the atmosphere, the Fediverse,

00:08:26.260 --> 00:08:28.360
and the web all at once.

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:30.900
It's really, really exciting to me.

00:08:30.900 --> 00:08:32.990
And I want to give a huge shout out to Leaflet

00:08:32.990 --> 00:08:35.970
Pocket and Offprint, who not only created standard.

00:08:35.970 --> 00:08:39.000
site, but also helped us a lot in the process of

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:40.480
us building standard.

00:08:40.480 --> 00:08:41.620
site into BridgeFed.

00:08:41.620 --> 00:08:44.840
I'm really excited to see people start using this.

00:08:44.840 --> 00:08:46.730
I'm already using it on my blog, and I've

00:08:46.730 --> 00:08:48.970
already heard from a few people who've started using it as

00:08:49.180 --> 00:08:49.330
well.

00:08:49.330 --> 00:08:50.900
So I'm super excited about this.

00:08:50.900 --> 00:08:53.130
I also want to take an opportunity to apologize to Jared.

00:08:53.130 --> 00:08:55.430
I don't think he's in the room, but Jared

00:08:55.430 --> 00:08:58.930
was at a conference in Europe, and he was about to

00:08:58.930 --> 00:09:00.350
promote Leaflet and standard.

00:09:00.350 --> 00:09:02.260
site, and then we exploded their app view.

00:09:02.260 --> 00:09:04.740
Like overnight, because we didn't tell him that we were

00:09:04.740 --> 00:09:07.780
doing this, and we just turned on our fire hose,

00:09:07.780 --> 00:09:08.870
and he was like, "Dude, what's happening

00:09:08.870 --> 00:09:10.070
with my app view?" He messaged me, I was

00:09:10.070 --> 00:09:11.720
like, "I don't think we did anything." And

00:09:11.720 --> 00:09:13.580
Ryan's like, "Yeah, we did." So yeah

00:09:13.580 --> 00:09:16.350
, I just wanted to publicly apologize to Jared, but we

00:09:16.350 --> 00:09:17.270
can just do things.

00:09:17.270 --> 00:09:18.260
So yeah, we did it.

00:09:18.260 --> 00:09:22.090
But yeah, so that's what we've done so much

00:09:22.090 --> 00:09:23.010
so far with BridgeFed.

00:09:23.010 --> 00:09:24.640
But one of the neat things we did with the standard.

00:09:24.640 --> 00:09:27.110
site integration is we actually made it way easier to add other

00:09:27.110 --> 00:09:29.070
lexicons to BridgeFed to bridge to the Fed

00:09:29.070 --> 00:09:29.700
iverse.

00:09:29.700 --> 00:09:32.320
And so if you're building a new product with its own

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:36.180
lexicon, and you think it deserves more distribution across

00:09:36.180 --> 00:09:38.570
these ecosystems across the web, across the Fediverse, please

00:09:38.570 --> 00:09:39.230
reach out to us.

00:09:39.230 --> 00:09:40.890
We've actually made it like dead easy.

00:09:40.890 --> 00:09:42.630
And we'd love to work with more people, and I

00:09:42.630 --> 00:09:45.390
think the distribution is really important to the users that are on

00:09:45.390 --> 00:09:46.130
your platforms.

00:09:46.130 --> 00:09:47.380
So we'd love to work with you.

00:09:47.380 --> 00:09:50.300
If you look at our GitHub, you might notice that we

00:09:50.300 --> 00:09:52.420
've also been playing around with some other protocols.

00:09:52.420 --> 00:09:54.280
Not going to talk too much about that today, but you

00:09:54.280 --> 00:09:56.420
can probably take a look and find out within a couple of

00:09:56.420 --> 00:09:57.140
minutes.

00:09:57.140 --> 00:09:59.620
Hopefully something to announce later this year.

00:09:59.620 --> 00:10:00.900
So that's BridgeFed.

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:02.660
Then there's Bounce.

00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:05.820
Bounce was a really exciting project, as I said before

00:10:05.820 --> 00:10:05.970
.

00:10:05.980 --> 00:10:08.490
But one of the limitations that we had in the original version

00:10:08.490 --> 00:10:11.110
of Bounce is you actually had to have an existing account

00:10:11.110 --> 00:10:12.260
at least on one side.

00:10:12.260 --> 00:10:13.810
So if you wanted to move from the Fediverse to the

00:10:13.810 --> 00:10:15.300
Atmosphere, you had to have an Atmosphere

00:10:15.300 --> 00:10:15.540
account.

00:10:15.540 --> 00:10:16.960
If you wanted to move from the Atmosphere to the

00:10:16.960 --> 00:10:18.790
Fediverse, you had to have a Fediverse account already

00:10:18.790 --> 00:10:18.980
.

00:10:18.980 --> 00:10:21.700
With the Fediverse, that doesn't matter as much because

00:10:21.810 --> 00:10:22.520
you can merge accounts.

00:10:22.520 --> 00:10:24.520
So if you had an Atmosphere account that was brid

00:10:24.520 --> 00:10:27.660
ged, we just merged the bridged version of your account

00:10:27.660 --> 00:10:27.990
in.

00:10:27.990 --> 00:10:29.620
But the other way is not possible.

00:10:29.620 --> 00:10:31.730
You cannot merge Atmosphere repos.

00:10:31.740 --> 00:10:34.690
And so we'd have to actually drop one of your accounts

00:10:34.690 --> 00:10:35.060
.

00:10:35.060 --> 00:10:37.360
And oftentimes that was the bridged version of the account.

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:39.370
So we actually had some users that migrated from the Atmos

00:10:39.370 --> 00:10:41.370
phere to the Fediverse and they wanted to go back.

00:10:41.370 --> 00:10:42.810
And we had no way to send them back.

00:10:42.810 --> 00:10:44.470
And it really, really sucked.

00:10:44.470 --> 00:10:47.040
But the reason we didn't launch with that was, for

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:50.700
one, Blue Sky wasn't allowing migrations back into their

00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:51.650
PDSs at that time.

00:10:51.650 --> 00:10:52.330
They do now.

00:10:52.330 --> 00:10:53.460
So that's changed.

00:10:53.460 --> 00:10:55.670
And the other thing that's changed since then is that there

00:10:55.670 --> 00:10:57.780
's just a lot more PDS providers, which is like

00:10:57.780 --> 00:10:58.980
just really exciting.

00:10:58.980 --> 00:11:01.200
Kudos to everyone running their own PDSs, people

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:02.900
running PDS migration services.

00:11:02.900 --> 00:11:04.910
We've taken a lot of inspiration from you guys.

00:11:04.910 --> 00:11:07.020
And so I'm really excited to announce that in the next

00:11:07.020 --> 00:11:09.350
couple of weeks, we're actually going to launch full mig

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:13.220
rations from the Fediverse to the Atmosphere, to

00:11:13.220 --> 00:11:16.020
any PDS that you want, whether that's Black Sky

00:11:16.020 --> 00:11:18.670
, Euro Sky, your own self-hosted of PD

00:11:18.670 --> 00:11:20.340
S or self-hosted social.

00:11:20.340 --> 00:11:21.090
It's your choice.

00:11:21.090 --> 00:11:22.770
You get to choose the PDS where you go and you

00:11:22.770 --> 00:11:25.540
can migrate all of your Fediverse followers in as you go

00:11:25.540 --> 00:11:25.700
.

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:27.460
Thank you.

00:11:27.460 --> 00:11:30.910
Yeah, personally, very excited.

00:11:30.910 --> 00:11:33.940
I really wanted to launch with that.

00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:35.380
But yeah, limitations were there.

00:11:35.380 --> 00:11:38.750
A cool byproduct of that, though, is that because

00:11:38.750 --> 00:11:40.860
we're able to move people to PDSs and Fed

00:11:41.220 --> 00:11:43.940
iverse accounts and merge Fediverse accounts, we can actually give

00:11:43.940 --> 00:11:46.020
people a credible exit from BridgyFed itself.

00:11:46.020 --> 00:11:48.340
There's a lot of other bridges and multi-protocol

00:11:48.340 --> 00:11:49.720
services out there now.

00:11:49.720 --> 00:11:53.360
And they also have tools like Bounce that are fully integrated

00:11:53.370 --> 00:11:54.260
into them.

00:11:54.260 --> 00:11:56.350
And so we want to give you the opportunity to be able

00:11:56.350 --> 00:11:58.610
to leave BridgyFed if one of those other services

00:11:58.610 --> 00:12:00.400
or platforms actually serves you better.

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:02.270
And so now you can actually split your BridgyFed

00:12:02.270 --> 00:12:04.680
account in half, create two native accounts, and then do

00:12:04.680 --> 00:12:05.770
what you will from there.

00:12:05.770 --> 00:12:06.570
It's your choice.

00:12:06.570 --> 00:12:07.610
It's your accounts.

00:12:07.610 --> 00:12:08.180
It's your life.

00:12:08.180 --> 00:12:10.580
So we're really excited to give people, finally, a

00:12:10.580 --> 00:12:12.180
credible exit from BridgyFed.

00:12:12.180 --> 00:12:13.680
We don't want to be the only people here.

00:12:13.680 --> 00:12:14.910
We don't want to be centralized.

00:12:14.910 --> 00:12:16.820
We want as many bridges out there as possible.

00:12:16.820 --> 00:12:18.460
So we're really excited to be able to give people that

00:12:18.570 --> 00:12:19.060
opportunity.

00:12:19.060 --> 00:12:22.270
The other thing that we're going to be launching later this

00:12:22.270 --> 00:12:24.820
year is being able to reconnect with unbridged follows.

00:12:24.820 --> 00:12:27.840
So when you bounce, we can bring all of your followers

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:28.500
with you.

00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:31.220
But anyone that isn't bridged, who you used to

00:12:31.220 --> 00:12:32.800
follow, we can't, you can't follow them.

00:12:32.950 --> 00:12:33.630
They're not bridged.

00:12:33.630 --> 00:12:35.380
They don't show up in your native account.

00:12:35.380 --> 00:12:36.340
So one of the things we're going to do to circum

00:12:36.340 --> 00:12:39.650
vent that is actually keep stock of all the users, that

00:12:39.650 --> 00:12:42.500
all of the people that you can no longer follow.

00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:44.430
And if they ever bridge that account in the future, we

00:12:44.430 --> 00:12:47.140
give you a notification so that you can immediately reconnect with them

00:12:47.140 --> 00:12:48.820
when they arrive natively to your platform.

00:12:49.030 --> 00:12:51.300
So we're getting closer.

00:12:51.300 --> 00:12:54.460
You can follow anyone from anywhere and leave for another platform at

00:12:54.460 --> 00:12:54.990
any time.

00:12:54.990 --> 00:12:56.900
And it's still kind of, but I think in the

00:12:56.900 --> 00:12:58.980
last year, we've done a pretty great job of making

00:12:59.120 --> 00:13:00.500
that kind of a whole lot smaller.

00:13:00.500 --> 00:13:03.150
There's also a whole bunch of APIs that we launched that

00:13:03.150 --> 00:13:05.340
I didn't get the chance to talk about here, that

00:13:05.340 --> 00:13:08.080
you can use a lot of these features natively in your

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:08.580
clients.

00:13:08.680 --> 00:13:10.580
So if you have a client and you're building on the

00:13:10.580 --> 00:13:12.410
social web, please reach out to us.

00:13:12.410 --> 00:13:14.280
You can actually make a lot of this stuff feel a lot

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:16.940
more native and make that kind of even smaller on your platform

00:13:16.940 --> 00:13:17.090
.

00:13:17.090 --> 00:13:18.580
So please reach out to us for that.

00:13:18.580 --> 00:13:21.300
Before I leave though, I know I'm running out of

00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:21.700
time.

00:13:21.700 --> 00:13:24.100
Sorry, I'm so sorry.

00:13:24.100 --> 00:13:25.060
I had so much to say.

00:13:25.060 --> 00:13:27.180
I had a bunch of dreams that I said last year that

00:13:27.180 --> 00:13:28.020
we accomplished.

00:13:28.020 --> 00:13:30.450
But if there's one thing that I've learned in the

00:13:30.450 --> 00:13:32.580
last year is that I need to dream a little bit bigger

00:13:32.580 --> 00:13:34.100
because Ryan is just insane.

00:13:34.260 --> 00:13:36.820
He can build literally anything I throw at him.

00:13:36.820 --> 00:13:37.860
So I'm going to dream way bigger.

00:13:37.860 --> 00:13:39.170
I didn't even tell Ryan I'm going to say this

00:13:39.170 --> 00:13:39.700
, by the way.

00:13:39.700 --> 00:13:45.080
Paul Frazee said something really interesting yesterday in his presentation

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:45.220
.

00:13:45.220 --> 00:13:48.180
He said that one of the biggest benefits of the atmosphere is

00:13:48.180 --> 00:13:50.900
that you have a single account that works across multiple different services

00:13:50.900 --> 00:13:52.900
and shares data across all of those services.

00:13:52.900 --> 00:13:55.220
I've been calling that the everything account.

00:13:55.220 --> 00:13:57.000
I'm not the only one that's been calling it everything

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:57.140
.

00:13:57.140 --> 00:13:59.620
I think Dame has been calling it the everything ecosystem.

00:13:59.620 --> 00:14:01.500
So like I'm not the only one saying this, but

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:03.630
I've been using the everything account because that's what's

00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:05.380
been making sense to me and some other folks.

00:14:05.380 --> 00:14:09.210
But the everything account isn't like an everything account.

00:14:09.210 --> 00:14:11.300
It's an everything account for the atmosphere.

00:14:11.300 --> 00:14:12.950
And with Bridgifed, if there's one thing

00:14:13.040 --> 00:14:15.380
that I've realized over the course of the last year is

00:14:15.380 --> 00:14:18.740
it can actually help make the atmosphere account and everything account for

00:14:18.740 --> 00:14:19.460
everything.

00:14:19.460 --> 00:14:21.220
And so my dream over the next few years, maybe it

00:14:21.220 --> 00:14:22.660
's going to be multi-year or maybe Ryan's going

00:14:22.660 --> 00:14:23.780
to push some code tonight.

00:14:24.900 --> 00:14:27.870
But my dream for the future is actually to make your atmosphere

00:14:27.870 --> 00:14:29.780
account, your everything account for everything.

00:14:29.780 --> 00:14:31.890
And so that's the mission that I'm on for the

00:14:31.890 --> 00:14:33.960
next few years with Ryan and the rest of the Anu

00:14:33.960 --> 00:14:34.580
Social team.

00:14:34.580 --> 00:14:36.090
So thank you guys very much.

00:14:36.090 --> 00:14:37.380
I'm sorry for going over.

00:14:37.380 --> 00:14:42.550
We are a non-profit with two full-time volunteers

00:14:42.550 --> 00:14:44.660
for the last year.

00:14:44.760 --> 00:14:46.990
So if you believe in our mission, please go to our

00:14:46.990 --> 00:14:48.050
Patreon, patreon.

00:14:48.050 --> 00:14:48.900
com/anusocial.

00:14:48.900 --> 00:14:52.470
You can get People's Not Platform merch on store.

00:14:52.870 --> 00:14:53.470
anu.

00:14:53.470 --> 00:14:54.970
social.

00:14:54.970 --> 00:14:56.420
And you can find me all over the atmosphere.

00:14:56.420 --> 00:14:57.250
Thank you guys so much.

00:14:57.250 --> 00:14:58.380
And I'm really sorry for taking away too much.
